<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06278240 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06278240 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SPORTS; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  College football was struck Thursday by the unexpected deaths of two players.;  Mississippi State defensive lineman Rodney Stowers, hospitalized Sunday inColumbus, Miss., for treatment of a broken leg, died of what doctors said waslung hemorrhaging associated with the injury. He was 20.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TWO FOOTBALL PLAYERS DIE UNEXPECTEDLY  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Sports Digest  </MEMO><TEXT>     In Huntington, W.Va., Marshall offensive lineman J.D. Coffman died of abacterial virus a day after he was taken ill. He was 19.; PRO BASKETBALL:Dallas Mavericks forward Roy Tarpley was cleared by his NBA-sanctioned drugafter-care program to join the team for the opening of practice today, and aformal lifting of his suspension could come today. . . . First-round draftpick Rich King, a 7-foot-2 center from Nebraska, signed a four-year contractwith Seattle. . . . New Jersey center Jack Haley, a restricted free agent,signed an offer sheet from the Los Angeles Lakers.; GOLF: Keith Clearwatershot a 7-under-par 63 to grab the first-round lead of the Texas Open in SanAntonio. Karl Kimball was second at 64, one stroke better than MarkCalcavecchia, who had two eagles in his first outing since his rough finalmatch in the Ryder Cup last weekend.; TENNIS: Wayne Ferreira stunned secondseed Ivan Lendl 6-4, 2-6, 7-5 in just under two hours in the third round ofthe Australian Indoors in Sydney. Top seed Stefan Edberg and No. 4 AndreAgassi won easily. . . . John McEnroe says he deserves a spot on the U.S.Davis Cup team that plays France next month in Lyon. &quot;I would love to playDavis Cup. I already won it four times,&quot; said McEnroe, who even offered toplay doubles. . . . Players representing seven area community colleges willcompete in a three-day tournament beginning today at West Valley College.Finals are scheduled to begin Sunday at 2 p.m.; MISCELLANY: Kevin Lowery ofSan Jose, Trooper Johnson of Sunnyvale, Dave Efferson of San Leandro and ChuckGill of San Francisco are among the 35 wheelchair basketball players invitedto try out Saturday and Sunday in Santa Clara for the U.S. team that will playin the 1992 Paralympic Games in Barcelona, Spain.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911004  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  371  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, October 4, 199100278240,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>